    <title>6.087-3-Control flow. Functions and modular programming. Variable scope. Static and global variables.</title>
    <url>/2022/03/07/6-087-3-Control-flow-Functions-and-modular-programming-Variable-scope-Static-and-global-variables/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="1-Blocks-and-Compound-Statements"><a href="#1-Blocks-and-Compound-Statements" class="headerlink" title="1. Blocks and Compound Statements"></a>1. Blocks and Compound Statements</h1><ul>
<li>block can substitute for simple statement</li>
<li>compiled as a single unit</li>
</ul>
<h1 id="2-Control-Flow"><a href="#2-Control-Flow" class="headerlink" title="2. Control Flow"></a>2. Control Flow</h1><ul>
<li>Unlike C++ or Java, C89&#x2F;C90 has no boolean type util C99.</li>
<li>Expression must be numeric (or a pointer)<figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">const char str[] = &quot;some text&quot;;</span><br><span class="line">if (str) // string is not null</span><br><span class="line">	return 0;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="2-1-Conditional-Statement"><a href="#2-1-Conditional-Statement" class="headerlink" title="2.1 Conditional Statement"></a>2.1 Conditional Statement</h2><ul>
<li><code>if</code> or <code>switch</code> statement</li>
<li>for <code>switch</code>, integer (or character) variable as input</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="2-2-Loops"><a href="#2-2-Loops" class="headerlink" title="2.2 Loops"></a>2.2 Loops</h2><ul>
<li><code>while</code> <code>for</code> <code>do-while</code> <code>break</code> <code>continue</code></li>
<li>for <code>for</code> loop, expressions can be empty, condition assumed to be “true”</li>
<li><code>break</code>: exits <strong>innermost</strong> loop or <code>switch</code> statement to exit early</li>
</ul>
<h1 id="3-Functions"><a href="#3-Functions" class="headerlink" title="3. Functions"></a>3. Functions</h1><ul>
<li>variables declared outside of a function block are globals</li>
<li>minimize transfer of state between functions</li>
</ul>
<h1 id="4-Modular-Programming"><a href="#4-Modular-Programming" class="headerlink" title="4. Modular Programming"></a>4. Modular Programming</h1><ul>
<li><code>extern</code> keyword<br>It’s a good habit to declare the global variable in .c file and then use extern in .h file.</li>
</ul>
<h1 id="5-Variable-Scope"><a href="#5-Variable-Scope" class="headerlink" title="5. Variable Scope"></a>5. Variable Scope</h1><h2 id="5-1-Static-Variables"><a href="#5-1-Static-Variables" class="headerlink" title="5.1 Static Variables"></a>5.1 Static Variables</h2><ul>
<li><code>static</code> keyword has two meanings, depending on where the static variable is declared</li>
</ul>
<ol>
<li><pre><code>Outside a function, `static` variables/functions only visible within that file, not globally (cannot be `extern`ed)
</code></pre>
</li>
<li><pre><code>Inside a function, `static` variables:
</code></pre>
</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>are still local to that function</li>
<li>are initialized only during program initialization</li>
<li>do not get reinitialized with each function call</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="5-2-Register-Variables"><a href="#5-2-Register-Variables" class="headerlink" title="5.2 Register Variables"></a>5.2 Register Variables</h2><ul>
<li>during execution, data processed in <code>registers</code></li>
<li>registers do not reside in addressed memory; pointer of a register variable illegal</li>
</ul>
